CARE aims to to meet the life-saving WASH and temporary shelter needs of the most vulnerable population, especially women and girls, affected by monsoon flooding in NRS by improving water and sanitation access and temporary shelter for 5,080 HH without access to clean water in Buthiduang and housing damages.

CARE India will carry out relief distribution (Shelter NFI*; WASH NFI and other Households items**) in Kumartchi block in Cuddalore district. This block is one among the six severely affected. Kumartchi also has more than 70% of Dalit population: this community has emerged as one of the most affected and vulnerable communities in the assessements conducted by the TN IAG, in which CARE also participated.

A hygiene Kit and water for human consumption will be provided per family of five members, benefiting 400 families (2,000 women, man, boys and girls) located in five communities affected by the emergency.

CARE plans to provide relief to the affected people in Supaul district through distribution of non-food items (NFI). As per CARE assessment in Supaul district, Marauna and Nirmali blocks are among the most affected. Supaul, Kisanpur, Saraigarh-Bhaptiyahi and Basantpur being the other four most affected in Supaul.CARE will carry out relief distribution viz. Shelter NFI*; WASH NFI. Based on the needs prioritised by affected community during the assessments, CARE will be providing assistance in WASH and Shelter.

As the basis upon which livelihoods depend, the governance and sustainable use of the natural resource base in the Sahel is critical for building climate resilience. The consortium proposes an innovative model that combines improvement of climate information services, sustainable and climate-resilient livelihood options, gender equality and sustainable natural resource management. This integrated approach builds on existing experience, while enabling learning, flexibility and innovation. The premise for success is greater understanding of risk, vulnerability and capacity in the face of climate change, more effective use of climate information for decision-making and strengthened local, national and cross-border governance and institutions.

CARE intervention will support 1,300 vulnerable IDPs households (about 7,800 persons) via cash distribution to cover immediate food needs in complement of dry food already distributed by WFP operations. In addition, CARE raising awareness sessions will benefit not only to IDPs but also host-families in both Districts, this will allow them to increase their knowledge towards gender issues such as gender based violence, nutrition and health practices but also contribute to reduce the risk of tension between both communities.
